04519nam a22006975i 9780812298413DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20222022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122984137 a10.9783/97808122984132doi  a(DE-B1597)590453  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aDD901.H28 7aHIS0140002bisacsh04a943/.5152231 aBerg, Anne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOn Screen and Off :bCinema and the Making of Nazi Hamburg /cAnne Berg. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (200 p.) :b15 b/w halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. Living Photography: Film and the City -- t2. On Screen: The Search for Authenticity -- t3. Off Screen: Führerstadt and the Limits of Social Control -- t4. Rubbled: Remnants of a Nazi City -- tEpilogue. Filmstadt Hamburg -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOn Screen and Off shows that the making of Nazism was a local affair and the Nazi city a product of more than models and plans emanating from Berlin. In Hamburg, film was key in turning this self-styled "Gateway to the World" into a "Nazi city." The Nazi regime imagined film as a powerful tool to shape National Socialist subjects. In Hamburg, those very subjects chanced upon film culture as a seemingly apolitical opportunity to articulate their own ideas about how Nazism ought to work. Tracing discourses around film production and film consumption in the city, On Screen and Off illustrates how Nazi ideology was envisaged, imagined, experienced, and occasionally even fought over.Local authorities in Hamburg, from the governor Karl Kaufmann to youth wardens and members of the Hamburg Film Club, used debates over cinema to define the reach and practice of National Socialism in the city. Film thus engendered a political space in which local activists, welfare workers, cultural experts, and administrators asserted their views about the current state of affairs, articulated criticism and praise, performed their commitment to the regime, and policed the boundaries of the Volksgemeinschaft. Of all the championed "people's products," film alone extended the promise of economic prosperity and cultural preeminence into the war years and beyond the city's destruction. From the ascension of the Nazi regime through the smoldering rubble, going to the movies grounded normalcy in the midst of rupture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aMotion picture industryzGermanyzHamburgxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion picturesxPolitical aspectszGermanyzHamburgxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion picturesxSocial aspectszGermanyzHamburgxHistoryy20th century. 0aNational socialism and motion pictures. 0aNational socialismzGermanyzHamburg. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh  aEuropean History.  aHistory.  aWorld History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076767440uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229841340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812298413423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780812298413/original  a978-3-11-076767-4  University of Pennsylvania Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK